irca 1341","about 1340":"circa 1340","1438":"1438","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"en":{"about 1316–":"about 1316–Deceased","1320–Female":"1320–Deceased","1338–Male":"1338–Deceased","1340–Male":"1340–Deceased","1341–1438":"1341–1438","1316–Male":"1316–Deceased","1316":"1316","1338":"1338","about 1316":"about 1316","about 1338":"about 1338","about 1337":"about 1337","1320":"1320","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","about 1341":"about 1341","about 1340":"about 1340","1438":"1438","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bromwich","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from West Bromwich (Staffs) or Castle and Little Bromwich (Warwicks)."],"variants":[{"name":"Brommage","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]},{"name":"Brumage","meanings":["English (Midlands): variant of   Bromage  ."]},{"name":"Bromage","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Worcestershire): habitational name from West Bromwich in Staffordshire, or Castle and Little Bromwich in Warwickshire, named in Old English with <i>brōm</i> ‘broom’ (the shrub) + <i>wīc</i> ‘outlying dairy farm’. Compare   Brumage  ."]},{"name":"Brimage","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Brumage  . This name is comparatively rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bromige","meanings":["English:  see  Bromwich  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Richard Bromwich was born about 1316, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom. He married Mrs. Richard Bromwich about 1337, in Gloucestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons."},"et":{"about 1316–":"umbes 1316–Surnud","1320–Female":"1320–Surnud","1338–Male":"1338–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1341–1438":"1341–1438","1316–Male":"1316–Surnud","1316":"1316","1338":"1338","about 1316":"umbes 1316","about 1338":"umbes 1338","about 1337":"umbes 1337","1320":"1320","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","about 1341":"umbes 1341","about 1340":"umbes 1340","1438":"1438","Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucestershire, England"},"fi":{"about 1316–":"noin 1316–Kuollut","1320–Female":"1320–Kuollut","1338–Male":"1338–Kuollut","1340–Male":"1340–Kuollut","1341–1438":"1341–1438","1316–Male":"1316–Kuollut","1316":"1316","1338":"1338","about 1316":"noin 1316","about 1338":"noin 1338","about 1337":"noin 1337","1320":"1320","1341":"1341","1340":"1340","about 1341":"noin 1341","about 1340